            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Related: [a new Private Mode which causes paste events to trigger unsolicited MIME type listings via the Kitty clipboard protocol](https://rockorager.dev/misc/bracketed-paste-mime/)\n\n> Detect binary content and pass a flag to vim.paste ?\n\n\n\nClipboard data tend to have many representations. For example when I copy an image from a web browser, the clipboard data will ahave a text representation (which is the URL of the image) that Nvim receives when users paste in TUI, alongside an `image` representation that is the blob of the image, and a few others\n\nSo I have 2 design proposals:\n\n#### Design 1\n- Add another phase to `vim.paste` (e.g. `0`). In that phase Nvim will pass a list of MIME types that the clipboard data has representations in as the first argument to `vim.paste`, and a dict `{id: string}` as the third argument. `vim.paste` return a string for the mimetype it wants to get, or false to cancel\n- If the `vim.paste` call for phase 0 returns a mimetype, Nvim UI will call `nvim_paste` with the first argument being a blob chunk corresponding to the mimetype, phase being 1, 2, 3, or -1, and `{id: string}` the same as one passed to `vim.paste` in phase 0 (needs #31903)\n(I think there needs to be id because any plugins could call `nvim_paste` while an image for example is being \"streamed\" by UI, which could break the image)\n\n#### Design 2\n- Also add a phase 0 for `vim.paste`, in that phase, Nvim pass a list of available MIME types.\n- Nvim provides a function to allow plugins to get clipboard data based on mimetype. The function signature could be like\n```lua\n---@param mimetype string\n---@param on_chunk fun(chunk: string, phase: 1|2|3|-1)\nfunction vim.ui.clipboard.get_data(mimetype, on_chunk)\n```\n\n(Btw I wonder why the first argument to `vim.paste` is a string array instead of just a string)",
